We have removed the 0 value from the price, bedroom and bathroom as there cannot be any houses with 0 bedroom, bathroom and price. We are not removing other 0 values from other columns as they can differ from house to house

Here in the following, we are calculating the age of the house, years since last renovation and some other info as they will give better insights about the dataset and houses.

In[159]:
# Get the current year
current_year = datetime.now().year

# 1. House Age
data['age_of_house'] = current_year - data['yr_built']

# 2. Time Since Last Renovation
data['years_since_last_renovation'] = np.where(data['yr_renovated'] == 0, 0, current_year - data['yr_renovated'])

# 3. Price per Square Foot
data['price_per_sqft_living'] = data['price'] / data['sqft_living']

# 4. Lot Size vs Living Space Ratio
data['lot_vs_living'] = data['sqft_lot'] / data['sqft_living']

# 5. Above Ground Space to Total Living Space Ratio
data['above_to_living_ratio'] = data['sqft_above'] / data['sqft_living']

Checking for Outliers and BoxPlot them

In[167]:
# Numerical columns
numerical_columns = [
    'bedrooms', 'bathrooms', 'floors', 'waterfront', 'view',
    'condition', 'sqft_basement', 'age_of_house',
    'years_since_last_renovation', 'price_per_sqft_living', 'lot_vs_living',
    'above_to_living_ratio'
]

# Step 1: Calculate IQR for each numerical column
outlier_summary = {}
for col in numerical_columns:
    Q1 = new_data[col].quantile(0.25)
    Q3 = new_data[col].quantile(0.75)
    IQR = Q3 - Q1
    lower_bound = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
    upper_bound = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR
    outliers = new_data[(new_data[col] < lower_bound) | (new_data[col] > upper_bound)]
    outlier_summary[col] = len(outliers)

# Step 2: Print outlier counts for each column
print("Outlier Count Summary:")
for col, count in outlier_summary.items():
    print(f"{col}: {count} outliers")

# Step 3: Visualize with box plots
plt.figure(figsize=(15, 10))
for i, col in enumerate(numerical_columns, 1):
    plt.subplot(4, 4, i)
    sns.boxplot(new_data[col], color="skyblue")
    plt.title(f"Boxplot of {col}")
    plt.xlabel(col)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Removing the Outliers

In[168]:
# Columns with outliers
columns_with_outliers = [
    'bedrooms', 'bathrooms', 'floors', 'waterfront', 'view',
    'condition', 'sqft_basement', 'age_of_house',
    'years_since_last_renovation', 'price_per_sqft_living', 'lot_vs_living',
    'above_to_living_ratio'
]

# Remove outliers
for col in columns_with_outliers:
    Q1 = new_data[col].quantile(0.25)
    Q3 = new_data[col].quantile(0.75)
    IQR = Q3 - Q1
    lower_bound = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
    upper_bound = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR
    # Filter rows within the IQR bounds
    new_data = new_data[(new_data[col] >= lower_bound) & (new_data[col] <= upper_bound)]

# Print the remaining data shape
print(f"Data shape after removing outliers: {new_data.shape}")

# Visualize again with box plots to verify outliers are removed
plt.figure(figsize=(15, 10))
for i, col in enumerate(columns_with_outliers, 1):
    plt.subplot(4, 4, i)
    sns.boxplot(new_data[col], color="skyblue")
    plt.title(f"Boxplot of {col} (Outliers Removed)")
    plt.xlabel(col)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

K-FOLD VALIDATION OF RANDOM FOREST MODEL WITH R_2 SCORE

In[220]:
# Features and target variable
x = new_data.drop(columns=['price'])
y = new_data['price']

# Define categorical columns
categorical_columns = ['country', 'waterfront', 'view', 'condition']

# Apply one-hot encoding to categorical features
x = pd.get_dummies(x, columns=categorical_columns, drop_first=True)

# Initialize KFold with 4 splits
kf = KFold(n_splits=4, shuffle=True, random_state=42)

# Store metrics for each fold
mse_scores = []
r2_scores = []
rmse_scores = []
index = 1

# Initialize Random Forest regression model
rf_model = RandomForestRegressor(n_estimators=100, random_state=42)
In[221]:
for train_index, test_index in kf.split(x):
    # Split data into training and testing sets for this fold
    x_train, x_test = x.iloc[train_index], x.iloc[test_index]
    y_train, y_test = y.iloc[train_index], y.iloc[test_index]

    # Fit the Random Forest regression model
    rf_model.fit(x_train, y_train)

    # Make predictions
    y_pred = rf_model.predict(x_test)
In[222]:
# Calculate metrics
mse = mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred)
rmse = np.sqrt(mse)
r2 = r2_score(y_test, y_pred)

# Append metrics
mse_scores.append(mse)
rmse_scores.append(rmse)
r2_scores.append(r2)

print(f'MSE in K-Fold {index} -> {mse}')
print(f'RMSE in K-Fold {index} -> {rmse}')
print(f'R2 in K-Fold {index} -> {r2}')
index += 1
print('-' * 50)

# Print the average metrics across all folds
print(f'Average MSE across 4 folds -> {np.mean(mse_scores)}')
print(f'Average RMSE across 4 folds -> {np.mean(rmse_scores)}')
print(f'Average R2 Score across 4 folds -> {np.mean(r2_scores)}')

Average MSE across 4 folds -> 8894098826.101305

# Split Data into Features and Target
X = new_data.drop(columns=['price'])

mae_xgb = mean_absolute_error(y_test, y_pred_xgb)
r2_xgb = r2_score(y_test, y_pred_xgb)

# Print Results for XGBoost
print("\nTuned XGBoost Model Evaluation:")
print(f"Mean Squared Error (MSE): {mse_xgb:.2f}")
print(f"Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE): {rmse_xgb:.2f}")
print(f"Mean Absolute Error (MAE): {mae_xgb:.2f}")
print(f"R-squared Score (R): {r2_xgb:.2f}")
